<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Wow.  Heh, ye really like the idea i3ullseye?  I'm glad ye thought it a plausible one, by all means repost it elsewhere.  Let em know where it came from, to appease my minor sense of ego.  *grin*<P>As for thoughts on balancing it, here's what I thought about later:<P>Agreed, the item should have hit points, and should fall to the ground when "defeated".  However, when lying on the ground, I think the durability (or whatever it is that lessens over use) should be at 0, so it has to be repaired.  Makes sense, right?  A shield gets beat to hell by all the swords you're forcing it to block, so ya gotta repair it to use it again.<P>My next idea is whether this should be the "one pet" we're allowed, or if we should be given both.  I really think that it should *not* count as our one-and-only-pet, but instead the controlled item should get it's own control window. And here's why:<P>This power will be Matter Specced (obviously. Telekinesis should be in the Telekinesis line).  However, the Charm spell line is in the Mind Spec.  So people who have Level 40+ pets will NOT be able to also control very powerful swords/shields.  So there's the balance.  Same goes for the other way, a person with a shield that blocks 60% of all attacks (a pretty high spec spell, I'll bet) will have a pretty craptacular pet.  Again, balanced.  And then you'll get the some people who even it out, and they'll have a mediocre sword and a mediocre pet.  Finally, very balanced.<P>When thinking on it this way, I think the Sword thing should be pretty powerful.  Not as powerful as pets, since Pets take so damn long to find and die so easily without an ability for us to heal them.  But the control spell line should be powerful enough that it's worth going in to (I expect the Shields would be the most popular, since a percentage of blocking hits would be really useful to someone who is a Body mage, and is nuking the hell outta people).  Plus, anyone who specs fully in Matter will not be as useful with either Nukes or Mezzes or Debuffs (which the other two lines give), so a full Matter Specced Sorcerer should feel that their flying sword or shield is worth it.  I expect, of course, there'll be more to Matter than just this, but the sword should hold it's own.  Not as well as charmed pets, but well enough.<P>If this does go in, I expect even Mind and Body Specced Sorcerers will put some into Matter, just so they can have the shield there floating for the added small percentage of defense.  I think that would be very common, indeed, just like some people put just enough into mind to get the first AE Mez.<P>I think this, coupled with the Force Wall idea someone threw around earlier (the idea of creating walls to hold back enemies, physical barriers that had to be destroyed perhaps like keep gates), and then the DoTs for damage, would make Matter quite the line to consider.  <P>Oh!  Another thought occured to me.  Should we allow Staves to be objects which can be Telekinesis-affected?  For one reason: our 40 Epic staff.  I know I certainly wouldn't wield the sucker, but I'd make use of it's Proc that no Sorcerer would ever really use themselves.  <P>~Sigma<BR>32 Sorcerer<BR>Percival
</FONT>
